data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The temporary `AllowSynchronousIO()` escape hatch that worked in .NET 10 no longer exists.

Every synchronous call in your repository — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

### The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- All return types wrap in `Task<T>` and methods become `async`

This will ripple up through your call chain — controllers/services calling these methods must also become async. The Cosmos SDK is inherently async, so this eliminates the hidden `Task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` deadlock risk that sync-over-async always carried.
